snippet.textDisplay:
Having been to White Island (1991), I will just say this:

White Island is a continuously active volcano. Whereas others go dormant for periods of years, decades or even centuries, White Island is continuously active in that it is constantly degassing and this continuous degassing is what helps to make the volcano relatively safe. What made the eruption happen in this instance was that the discharge of vapour helps to weld the rock in the vent together and if this welding process goes on long enough, the vent seals over - the volcano has not gone dormant, but rather, it has corked itself. With the vent blocked a clearing event that is unpredictable in size, timing and power becomes more likely.

White Island began showing increasing signs of unrest. In late November it was upgraded to Alert Level 2 signalling that activity had increased. Whilst not unusual for White Island to do this, the language of the GeoNet bulletins got stronger a few days before the eruption, suggesting that they thought there was now a distinct possibility of an explosion. And that is precisely what happened on Monday.

GeoNet cannot make the decisions on whether pleasure craft or helicopters visit the island or not. But its warnings are based on an assessment of the data from three seismometers, a camera and a microphone on the island and in the days before the eruption GeoNet recorded substantial increases in visible discharge as well as seismic activity.

Before we have a conversation about whether tourists should be allowed back, or whether we stop tourist activities, let us help the authorities finish the search, help the injured and the families of the deceased. These things are necessary now so that we can move on, but also so that when the time for these conversations DOES come, we are ready.

snippet.textDisplay:
I can totally understand why people go there. I travel to Japan regularly and in 2018 I was lucky enough to see Sakurajima erupt when we were at an observatory on the volcano about 1,5km away from the crater. Seeing this huge ash cloud rising into the air was the greatest thing I have ever seen. In the night it probably erupted again because it was raining ash the next morning and everything got covered in a thin layer of ash.
We continued to to Mount Aso, another volcano. There the station of the cable car next to the crater was totally destroyed from a prior eruption. Scary, but too fascinating to say no. The chance to be there while it erupts is zero.
We also planed to go to Kirishima. There are like 5 craters within a 5km circle. There are supposed to be some nice hiking trails. But we couldn't got because one volcano erupted a few months before and authorities established a no entry zone around the volcanos which also affected the hiking trails.

snippet.textDisplay: One of the people who have gone missing following the eruption is Zoe Hosking, one of my best childhood friends. I have fond memories of the two of us sleeping over at each others houses as kids, making homemade pizza and watching Tangled over and over again until we fell asleep. Never in a million years would I have thought that I would be being told by my parents today that she might be dead. Zoe’s father Gavin is also missing, her mother Lisa suffering severe burns in hospital. Lisa was also a close family friend of ours; my mum and her often went out to get coffee together after dropping Zoe and I off to school. It’s come as a shock to everyone in the community to learn of the tragedy that has happened on White Island - this was supposed to be the adventure of a lifetime for their family.  If you’re out there, Zoe, I miss you. Please stay safe. ❤️

``Depart from Tauranga airport for a scenic helicopter flight and guided tour of White Island. Walk in the crater of New Zealand's most active volcano. See bubbling mud pools, roaring volcanic vents, steaming sulphur lake and desolate mining ruins.``

Cost per person : US$ 645.

US$ 645 is why the tourists were allowed to be there.

`..bubbling mud pools, roaring volcanic vents, steaming sulphur lake..` is not a stroll along the beach at sunset.

You pays your money and takes your chances.

snippet.textDisplay: I mean in no way to be callous, but why do some people love to stand on the very edge of disaster? What were they doing on White Island, anyway? This tragedy reminds me of when Kilauea erupted just a year ago! Everyone who lost everything lived right on top of the lava tube that blew up. Why?? The whole place is littered with earlier lava flows and craters. Can no one catch a clue? I am finding it hard to feel 100% sympathetic for the White Island victims; they more or less asked for it.
